{
  "paraphrase_corpus": "The goal of this research was to identify the minimum cortical bone thickness needed for precise measurement of its material density using computed tomography (CT) and to set up standard reference values. To mimic different cortical thicknesses, a phantom was created with various thicknesses of a bone-like substance. The density for each thickness level was recorded using a GE 9800 CT scanner and the OsteoQuant, a CT scanner specifically designed for bone density measurements in limbs. The essential minimum thickness for accurate density measurement was established for each device. In addition, CT scans were used to assess the material density and cortical thickness in the radius and/or femur of 761 healthy individuals aged between 4 to 84 years. It was found that a minimum thickness of 2-2.5 mm was necessary for accurate assessment of the phantom walls by CT; beneath this threshold, density values decreased linearly with width. In human subjects, as long as the cortical thickness was more than 2-2.5 mm, the density of cortical bone in the limbs was consistent across all participants, unaffected by their height or weight. Cortical thickness appeared to increase until the age of 30 and then began to decline after age 50. The study concludes that CT can reliably measure the material density of cortical bone in the limbs if the cortical layer is thicker than 2-2.5 mm.",
  "named_entities": ["computed tomography (CT)", "GE 9800 CT scanner", "OsteoQuant", "cortical bone", "appendicular skeleton"]
}

