{
  "paraphrase_corpus": "The main causes of illness and death in patients with thalassemia are due to iron overload cardiomyopathy (IOC). The disruption of cardiac cell internal calcium ([Ca<sup>2+</sup>]<sub>i</sub>) balance plays a central role in the development of heart failure associated with IOC. While the cardioprotective benefits of deferiprone (DFP) and N-acetylcysteine (NAC) are known, their impacts on [Ca<sup>2+</sup>]<sub>i</sub> transients and the expression of calcium-regulating proteins in the hearts of thalassemic mice have not been explored. This study induced iron overload in both wild-type (WT) and heterozygous &#946;-thalassemic (HT) mice through a diet high in iron. The mice with iron overload were then treated with either a control vehicle, DFP, NAC, or a combination of DFP and NAC. For WT and HT mice with iron overload, both DFP and NAC effectively reduced non-transferrin-bound iron in the blood, lowered the concentration of iron in the heart (CIC), and improved systolic function. The combined treatment with DFP and NAC was more effective than either treatment alone in lowering CIC and in better restoring the amplitude and rate of rise of cardiac [Ca<sup>2+</sup>]<sub>i</sub> transients. However, none of the treatments altered the expression of cardiac Ca<sup>2+</sup>-regulatory proteins. This research first demonstrates the additive effect of combined iron chelator and antioxidant therapy in managing [Ca<sup>2+</sup>]<sub>i</sub> regulation in the hearts of mice with thalassemia and iron overload, showing a consistent improvement in heart muscle function.",
  "named_entities": ["thalassemia", "iron overload cardiomyopathy (IOC)", "deferiprone (DFP)", "N-acetylcysteine (NAC)", "cardiac [Ca<sup>2+</sup>]<sub>i</sub> transient", "cardiac iron concentration (CIC)"]
}

{
  "paraphrase_corpus": "Biomarkers serve as critical instruments, offering essential insights into the intricate series of events and molecular processes at play in the pathophysiology of traumatic brain injury (TBI). By profiling various biomarker categories that reflect the fundamental pathological processes, it's possible to detect and understand both the initial damage and subsequent pathological sequences. Therefore, biomarkers are seen as valuable supplements for enhancing diagnostic accuracy, monitoring disease evolution and activity, steering molecularly targeted treatments, and assessing the effectiveness of interventions in TBI cases. Over the last quarter-century, considerable efforts have been dedicated to discovering new biomarkers. Despite these efforts, the application of brain injury markers in medical settings has sparked considerable debate, primarily due to the variability in regulatory standards and the absence of solid evidence confirming their analytical reliability and clinical relevance. This document provides an in-depth review of the currently known markers, highlighting their potential roles and uses in diagnosing, monitoring, pharmaceutical research, and clinical trials related to TBI. Throughout this discussion, we examine the recent integration of brain injury biomarkers into diagnostic protocols and explore future directions for validating these markers for clinical application.",
  "named_entities": ["Biomarkers", "traumatic brain injury (TBI)", "pathophysiology", "diagnostic guidelines", "clinical trials"]
}

