  "paraphrase_corpus": "Preeclampsia/eclampsia, also referred to as toxemia during pregnancy, continues to be a major concern among the three key complications in obstetrics. The prognosis for both the preeclamptic woman and her baby has seen improvement thanks to advancements in understanding the physiology of the uteroplacental-fetal system and the physiological abnormalities present in preeclampsia. Despite these advances, the underlying cause of preeclampsia is still not known. The implementation of meticulous screening for women susceptible to preeclampsia, coupled with prompt identification and management, has the potential to lower the rates of stillbirths, premature births, and maternal fatalities. This document also explores current theories on the pathophysiology of preeclampsia and outlines the nursing care required during the antepartum and intrapartum stages.",
