{
  "paraphrase_corpus": "Image symmetry robustly triggers the activation of extrastriate visual regions. The understanding of how symmetry is represented at the level of objects, as opposed to the level of images, remains limited. In this study, we explored the brain's electrophysiological reactions to symmetry in situations where it is inferred through amodal completion of shapes partially hidden by occlusion. Across four studies involving 112 participants, we employed a consistent experimental setup. Initially, an abstract shape, either symmetric or not, was shown for 250 ms (t0). Subsequently, a large rectangle obscured the shape completely for another 250 ms (t1), before shifting to a side to disclose a portion of the shape previously concealed (t2, lasting 1000 ms). It's noteworthy that at t2, symmetry could not be discerned directly from the visual information on the retina. In half of the test scenarios, the revealed shape was identical to the one first shown, while in the other half, a new shape was introduced. Tasks varied across experiments: participants assessed shape similarity (Experiments 1 and 2), color (Experiment 3), or the orientation of a triangle placed on the shapes (Experiment 4). The initial presentation of the shapes (from t0 to t1) consistently induced automatic symmetry-specific responses in the brain's electrical activity in all experiments. Crucially, there was a symmetry response linked to the frequency of exposure to shapes recognized as familiar when revealed from occlusion at t2. Experiments 2 and 4 verified that the second electrical response (at t2) did not simply result from an ongoing effect initiated at t0. Our findings suggest that the network in the brain responsible for processing visual symmetry can form an abstract representation of symmetry for objects even when they are not fully visible, provided these objects have been previously perceived as complete entities.",
